elements.contents: ... that the traditional Rapa Nui tattoos of Viriamo (pictured) included motifs similar to an adze and a paddle?

elements.title: Littlehampton libels
elements.contents: ... that in the Littlehampton libels, Edith Swan fooled three juries and two judges, had another woman sent to prison twice, and was declared not guilty before finally being convicted?

elements.title: Filomena Fortes
elements.contents: ... that Filomena Fortes once said that she was "a bit critical of top-level sports in Cape Verde" despite being the president of its National Olympic Committee?

elements.title: did likewise
elements.contents: ... that on the same day that the members of Heaven's Gate died in a mass suicide, five members of an unrelated group did likewise?

elements.title: Verna Mersereau
elements.contents: ... that American stage actress Verna Mersereau performed her traditional classical dances before royalty in Calcutta?

elements.title: 48th Hong Kong International Film Festival
elements.contents: ... that the 48th Hong Kong International Film Festival canceled the screening of a politically themed film due to the "inability to locate suitable copies", despite the film having been showcased three years earlier?

elements.title: Jumbo's
elements.contents: ... that the owners of Jumbo's claimed it became the first white-owned restaurant in Miami to serve and employ black people in the late 1960s?

elements.title: Gerda Philipsborn
elements.contents: ... that Gerda Philipsborn, a German woman, dedicated her life to the development of Jamia Millia Islamia, a national university in New Delhi?

elements.title: broke into a courthouse and began moving it
elements.contents: ... that one 1886 night 150 people broke into a courthouse and began moving it 15 miles (24 km), before getting stuck in a blizzard?
